observations.recommendation:
16. Direct the Supply Officer to determine the lot number, location and land area of those parcels of land without details and incorporate the details in their respective Property Card. Also, provide the Accounting Unit of such details for incorporation in their respective Property Ledger Card for easy reconciliation and to avoid double recording in the books of accounts;

17. Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Supply Officer to coordinate with the Municipal Assessor to locate/retrieve necessary legal documents for lands owned by the LGU to facilitate the titling of these lands; and

18. Prioritize and fast-track the titling of these lands by allocating funds for expenses to be incurred in the processing of TCT of the above lands.

21. Propose an amendment on the Local Revenue Code of the LGU through passing of Ordinance to require the submission of audited financial statements and/or monthly, quarterly or annual income tax returns of the preceding taxable year to provide a more reliable basis for assessment of business taxes;

22. Prior to business renewal period, gather Alphalist of Payees subjected to Expanded Withholding Tax and/or List of Purchases procured by the Municipality and/or Barangays from business establishments registered under their jurisdiction, and upon receipt of business renewal applications, conduct verification and compare the gross sales declared in the sworn statement of business establishments to ensure that the declared gross sales are true and correct;

23. Propose to the local treasurer’s league data sharing agreement to assist on the proper assessment of business taxes; 

24. Conduct examination on books of accounts once in a year prioritizing those business establishments with under declaration for an effective enforcement and collection of taxes, fees and charges as provided in the Ordinance; and

25. Consider imposing sanctions to business establishments in committing false attestation in the sworn statement and/or under-declaration of gross sales, in accordance with Local Revenue Code.

Require the GAD Focal Point System to:

30. Update the GAD Database to contain gender analysis identifying gender issues and determine gender-responsive PPAs for prioritization in programming and budgeting in the annual GPB in accordance with Annex B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No.2013-01;

31. Prepare the LGU GAD Agenda based from the results of gender analysis conducted on the GAD Database and/or any other gender analysis tools;

32. Prepare the annual GPB in accordance with the provisions of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No.2013-01, as amended by JMC No.2016-01 and include priority gender issues identified in the GAD Agenda; and

33. Undergo seminars and trainings to equip them with proper knowledge to effectively implement the GAD concepts, processes, rules and regulations.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:

Require the concerned Accountable Officer to submit the accounts and financial reports to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to the timelines of the abovementioned existing law, rules and regulations; 

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers, payrolls, official receipts, including the corresponding reports for each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month or pursuant to the abovementioned pertinent provisions of rules and regulations, as applicable; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the timelines on the recording and submission of accounts to the Auditor within ten days of the ensuing month; and

Identify and address the cause/s for the poor performance in the submission of monthly financial reports/accounts.

We recommended that Management make the necessary confirmation with concerned agencies whose names still appear in the listing of outstanding funds which remained in the books of the Municipality to ascertain the action to be taken onwards, viz: 

Return to the concerned source agencies the unutilized balance of the fund transfer wherein the agreement requires the return thereof; 

Revert to Government Equity the balances of fund transfers in the nature of financial assistance and subsidy wherein the agreement does not mention of the disposition of the unused balance and that future utilization thereof will be subject to the usual accounting, auditing and budgeting laws, rules and regulations; 

Retain special purpose funds; and  

Clean the books of accounts, particularly the accounts Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 in order to present fairly the Liability accounts in the financial statements.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that Management:

Send demand letter to concerned officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances requesting immediate settlement thereof;
In case of failure to settle the cash advance after two demand letters, withhold the payment of salaries of the concerned accountable officer to enforce settlement thereof;
Before processing a claim for cash advance, the Municipal Accountant shall ensure that the previous cash advance of the concerned official or employee has been settled;
The Municipal Accountant shall strictly monitor that all cash advances granted are liquidated within the required period of settlement;
Submit a copy of the demand letter issued to the ICO-Municipal Treasurer together with pertinent documents to prove its settlement, if any; and
Require the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to immediately settle all unliquidated cash advances. She shall maintain a record of all cash advances received and liquidated to serve as a ready reference in determining the unliquidated balance per cash advance received so as to prevent the accumulation of long outstanding cash advances.

We recommended that Management:

Apply or renew the contracts of insurance with the GSIS to ensure security and financial assurance in the event of unforeseen circumstances that could have a potential adverse impact on the government properties;
Properly monitor the insurance of all properties with the GSIS to avoid payment of unnecessary penalties, surcharges and damages to third party liabilities in case of vehicular accidents;
Properly accomplish the RPCPPE by providing the essential information of each motor vehicle to facilitate timely monitoring of insurance with the GSIS; and
Ensure that properties with insurance policies are existing properties of the Municipality and therefore be included in the RPCPPE.

Recommendations
We recommended, and the management agreed to direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Propose an amendment on the Local Revenue Code of the LGU through passing of Ordinance to require the submission of audited financial statements and/or monthly, quarterly or annual income tax returns of the preceding taxable year to provide a more reliable basis for assessment of business taxes;
Prior to business renewal period, gather Alphalist of Payees subjected to Expanded Withholding Tax and/or List of Purchases procured by the Municipality and/or Barangays from business establishments registered under their jurisdiction, and upon receipt of business renewal applications, conduct verification and compare the gross sales declared in the sworn statement of business establishments to ensure that the declared gross sales are true and correct.
Propose to the local treasurer’s league data sharing agreement to assist on the proper assessment of business taxes;
Conduct examination on books of accounts once in a year prioritizing those business establishments with under declaration for an effective enforcement and collection of taxes, fees and charges as provided in the Ordinance;
Consider imposing sanctions to business establishments in committing false attestation in the sworn statement and/or under-declaration of gross sales, in accordance with Local Revenue Code.

Recommendations
We recommended, and the management agreed to require the GAD Focal Point System to:
Update the GAD Database to contain gender analysis identifying gender issues and determine gender-responsive PPAs for prioritization in programming and budgeting in the annual GPB in accordance with Annex B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No.2013-01;
Prepare the LGU GAD Agenda based from the results of gender analysis conducted on the GAD Database and/or any other gender analysis tools;
Prepare the annual GPB in accordance with the provisions of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No.2013-01, as amended by JMC No.2016-01 and include priority gender issues identified in the GAD Agenda; and
Undergo seminars and trainings to equip them with proper knowledge to effectively implement the GAD concepts, processes, rules and regulations.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:

The Property Officer to maintain LRNPCs for all roads and its components in accordance with the prescribed format;

The Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain LRNLCs for roads and road components for every road network in accordance with the prescribed format and to reconcile the same with the LRNPCs and the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year;

The Municipal Accountant to ensure that only depreciable road components are subjected to depreciation and prepare the adjusting entry for the recorded depreciation expenses on road lots; and

The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system of the LGU in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment;

to identify critical processes and functions;

to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;

to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;

to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and

to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

Further, we recommended that members of the working group be capacitated by allowing them to attend seminars trainings on the formulation of the PSCP.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management:

Send demand letter to concerned officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances requesting immediate settlement thereof;

In case of failure to settle the cash advance after two demand letters, withhold the payment of salaries of the concerned accountable officer to enforce settlement thereof;

